der No and Item combination, which aligns with the request delivery dates.\n\nLooking at 1006-B Screw more closely, the request delivery dates across lines 1, 2, and 5 are scattered (Oct 6, Jan 7, Oct 6), but the instruction prioritizes line 1 first with 100 pcs, suggesting FIFO operates by line number rather than request date when the order issued date is constant. Since all lines within the same Order No share the same issued date, the system defaults to sequential line ordering for allocation.\n\nNow I'm working through the stock allocation calculations for each Order No and item combination, summing available stock from Sheet2 and distributing it across lines in order until stock runs out. Continuing through the rest of the inventory, I'm tracking how the remaining stock of 1006-B screws gets allocated across rows 12 and 13, fulfilling 100 units in the first request and 20 in the second before running out. The remaining items—1006-B in other variants, 1007-C, and 1008-D—all have zero stock, so they can't fulfill any of their line requests.\n\nNow I'm verifying the calculated allocation column against the pre-filled values, and the results match perfectly across all rows.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4368,"cache_read_input_tokens":14332,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4368},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fc6cc8cd-1337-4c0f-bd5f-197d5412e284","uuid":"9affc444-947a-419f-a8bf-90e0de94be31"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TmfUtzqE8J7dguPCy6ZJta","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WTCnMKy1pdJ3A5Y6QEzEAn","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 << 'PYEOF'\nimport openpyxl\nfrom collections import defaultdict\n\nwb = openpyxl.load_workbook('input.xlsx')\nws1 = wb['Sheet1']\nws2 = wb['Sheet2']\n\n# Build stock per (Order No, Item) from Sheet2\nstock = defaultdict(int)\nfor row in ws2.iter_rows(min_row=2, max_row=ws2.max_row, values_only=True):\n    order_no, item_code, item, qty = row[0], row[1], row[2], row[3]\n    if order_no and item and qty:\n        stock[(order_no, item)] += qty\n\nprint(\"Stock:\", dict(stock))\n\n# Read Sheet1 rows\nrows = []\nfor r in range(2, 19):\n    order_no = ws1.cell(r, 1).value\n    line = ws1.cell(r, 2).value\n    item = ws1.cell(r, 5).value\n    qty = ws1.cell(r, 7).value\n    rows.append((r, order_no, line, item, qty))\n\n# Group by (Order No, Item) and allocate by line number order\nfrom itertools import groupby\n\n# Sort by (Order No, Item, Line) for grouping\nsorted_rows = sorted(rows, key=lambda x: (x[1], x[3], x[2]))\n\nresults = {}\nfor key, group in groupby(sorted_rows, key=lambda x: (x[1], x[3])):\n    available = stock.get(key, 0)\n    for r, order_no, line, item, qty in group:\n        alloc = min(qty, available)\n        available -= alloc\n        results[r] = alloc\n\n# Write results\nfor r in range(2, 19):\n    ws1.cell(r, 8).value = results[r]\n    print(f\"Row {r}: {ws1.cell(r,1).value} Line {ws1.cell(r,2).value} {ws1.cell(r,5).value} Qty={ws1.cell(r,7).value} -> {results[r]}\")\n\nwb.save('output.xlsx')\nprint(\"\\nSaved output.xlsx\")\nPYEOF\n","description":"Compute stock allocation and save output.xlsx"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4368,"cache_read_input_tokens":14332,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemer